[[Category:Pages without translation templates]] [[en:Ōmuro Kofun group]]<!--enwiki derived wikidata interwikis--> {{Commons category|Omuro Kofun Group (Nagano)}} [[ja:大室古墳群 (長野市)]] {{wikidata link|Q11434367}}

{{afc comment|Wikidata entry [[d:Q11434367]] Wikidata name: Ōmuro Kofun group [[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 10:39, 11 June 2025 (UTC)}} {{Short description| part_of of Kofuns}} {{Infobox ancient site | name = Ōmuro Kofun Group | native_name =大室古墳群 | native_name_lang = | image =大室古墳群244号墳.JPG|image= File:大室古墳群244号墳.JPG| image_size = | alt = | caption = Kofun No.244 is the largest in the Ōmuro Kofun Group | map_type = Japan Nagano Prefecture#Japan | map_alt = location in Japan | relief = 1 | map_caption = Ōmuro Kofun Group | map_size = 270px | altitude_m = | altitude_ref = | coordinates ={{coord|36|35|23|N|138|13|51|E|display=inline, title}}; {{Coord|36.58972222|N|138.23083333|E|region:JP_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}| map_dot_label = | location =[[:en:Nagano, Nagano|Nagano, Nagano]], [[:en:Japan|Japan]]; {{ill|Nagano|qid=Q128849}}| region = [[:en:Chubu region|Chubu region]] | type = [[kofun]] | part_of = | length = | width = | area = | volume = | diameter = | circumference = | height = | built = | abandoned = | epochs = [[Kofun period]] | cultures = | discovered = | excavations = | archaeologists = | condition = | ownership = | management = | public_access = Yes (archaeological park) | Historic Site = | website = | architectural_styles = | architectural_details = | notes = }} {{nihongo|'''Ōmuro Kofun Group'''|大室古墳群|Ōmuro kofun-gun}} is a group of late ''[[Kofun period]]'' [[kofun|Kofun]]s located in the [[:en:Matsushiro, Nagano|Matsushiro]] neighborhood of the city of [[:en:Nagano, Nagano|Nagano]] in the [[:en:Chubu region|Chubu region]] of [[:en:Japan|Japan]]. The site was collectively designated a [[Monuments of Japan|National Historic Site of Japan]] in 1997.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://bunka.nii.ac.jp/heritages/detail/162751 |title=大室古墳群 |language=Japanese |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=}}</ref>
==Overview== The Ōmuro Kofun Group is a large [[:en:Necropolis|Necropolis]] consisting of over 500 tumuli spread across two valleys on the south side of the [[:en:Chikuma River|Chikuma River]] at an elevation of 350 to 500 meters approximately six kilometers southeast of Nagano city. The tombs were built over a 250-year period from the 5th to the 8th centuries. They have been grouped by archaeologists into five groups ( Kanaiyama, Kitatani, Kajo, Omurodani, and Kitayama) by their geographic location, stretching across an area of roughly 2.5 square kilometers. <ref name="Shiseki">{{cite book |last1=Isomura |first1=Yukio |last2=Sakai |first2=Hideya |title=(国指定史跡事典) National Historic Site Encyclopedia |date=2012 |publisher=学生社 |isbn=4311750404}}{{in lang|ja}}</ref>
There is only one [[:en:Keyhole-shaped kofun|keyhole-shaped ''kofun'']] ({{nihongo|''zenpō-kōen-fun''|前方後円墳|lt=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|comment=doing this because I need to differentiate it in piped links too with my new interwiki tool as not the ambiguous phrase keyhole shaped kofun|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=[[Zenpokoenfun]]|2=前方後円墳|3=|4=}}), but at least 330 smaller {{ill|Round Kofun|lt=circular-shaped ''kofun''|ja|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} ({{nihongo|''empun''|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun}}) made of stacked river stones from the Chikuma River. Most of these {{ill|Round Kofun|lt=circular-shaped ''kofun''|ja|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} have a diameter of approximately ten meters, and there is no other Kofun cluster in Japan where there are so many such {{ill|Round Kofun|lt=circular-shaped ''kofun''|ja|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} in such a small area. These mounds can be divided into 40 different variations, some with a scallop-shaped stone [[:en:Burial chamber|Burial chamber]], or with a triangular gabled burial chamber ceiling. Theories that these tombs were built by immigrants to Japan from the ancient Korean states of [[:en:Goguryeo|Goguryeo]] or [[:en:Baekje|Baekje]] remain controversial. Excavated [[:en:Grave good|Grave good]]s include [[:en:Sue pottery|Sue pottery]] and [[:en:Haji pottery|Haji pottery]] pottery, [[:en:Bronze mirror|Bronze mirror]]s, armor, swords, horse fittings and jewelry. The number of horse bones found was unusually large, and included the skull of a horse which was buried in the vestibule of one of the horizontal burial chambers. <ref name="Shiseki"/>
The site is now an [[:en:Archaeological park|Archaeological park]] with a museum, the {{nihongo| '''Ōmuro Kofun Museum'''|大室古墳館|Ōmuro kofun-kan}} displaying some of the artifacts discovered. <ref name="Shiseki"/>
==Access== *By car, 15 minutes from the Nagano IC on the [[:en:Jōshin-etsu Expressway|Jōshin-etsu Expressway]] *By bus, 20 minutes on foot from {{nihongo|Ōmuro Station|大室駅|Ōmuro eki}} (there are sign posts from the bus stop). From [[:en:East Japan Railway Company|East Japan Railway Company]] [[:en:Nagano Station|Nagano Station]], take the [[:en:Nagano Electric Railway|Nagaden Bus]], No. 8, the Suzaka-Yashima Line, departing from the south exit of Nagano Station.
